According to Dio Cassius, street-rioting by the partisans of the candidates was the cause. As Cicero received the votes of all the eenturies (cunctis suffragiis, de Off. 2, 17, 59), his name was proclaimed first (primus or primo loco renuntiatus) by the presiding magistrate, as there could be no doubt about his election. The claims of the other candidates were being decided by the counting of the votes (diribitio) when the interruption occurred.
